@NODE "Introduction" "Introduction"

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}
  @{b}============@{ub}

     This is a Monitor/Video hardware testing tool. It allows you to tune your
  monitor for best picture quality and at the same time test it for quality if
  you are buying one.  In fact this tool was  made because  there was  no such
  tool found for an Amiga computer that worked on most hardware.

     Tested on ECS/AGA/CGX/P96  and  000/020/030/040/060/UAE systems  and will
  probably  work with other more exotic  RTG software.  Tried @{"resolution" LINK "What_is_Resolution"} from
  320x200 up to 2048x1536 - the maximum  I managed  to get  from a  BVisionPPC
  card  that my monitor could handle!

                                 @{b}WARNING!
     Do not abuse your hardware, I take no responsibility if you brake it!@{ub}

     Some features of Monitor Test:

     - Can be run from Workbench or from command line

     - User friendly interface

     - Runs on any video hardware ECS/AGA/CyberGraphX/Picasso96

     - Supports all @{"colour" LINK "What_are_Colours"} depths up to 24 bit

     - The only tool of this kind on our beloved Amiga ?  Not anymore.

     Use the start-up test  pattern regularly to check the  picture quality of
  your  monitor.  It is highly recommended to use it at  least when you change
  the  @{"resolution" LINK "What_is_Resolution"}  or  @{"colours" LINK "What_are_Colours"}!   For final adjustments use the @{"geometry" LINK "Geometry_Tools"} and
  @{"brightness" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} test patterns of this program.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Requirements" "Requirements"

  @{b}Requirements@{ub}
  @{b}============@{ub}

     This is a special version of Monitor Test for 16:9 screens,  so you
  need a monitor or a projector that can display such screen modes and a
  good monitor prefs file for your video hardware with suitable settings.

  HDTV LCD (Tested with Samsung) and
  Plasma monitors (Tested with Panasonic)
  can handle the following 16:9 resolutions:

   720 x  400

   848 x  480 old plasma screens for 16:9 DVD's

  1280 x  720

  1360 x  768
  1368 x  768 some plasma screens have only 1366 physical pixels!

  1920 x 1080 also know as Full HDTV (Workbench looks nice ;-) )


  Minimum configuration:

  - an Amiga with a 68000 CPU
  - AmigaOS 3.0 (2.x ?)
  - 512 KB RAM


  Recommended configuration:

  - A fast CPU would help
  - AmigaOS 3.1
  - Hi resolution video card and monitor
  - 4 MB RAM or more


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Usage" "Usage"

  @{b}Usage@{ub}
  @{b}=====@{ub}

     Monitor Test can be run from Workbench or from command line. After
  starting the program a requester will appear. Select a screenmode and
  you  are  there!   Then you can press @{"buttons" LINK "Tools"} to see all the offered
  tests,  some @{"buttons" LINK "Tools"} have several tests so you have to click them in
  a row to cycle them.

     It is recommended to use a  screenmode  with at least 256 @{"colours" LINK "What_are_Colours"}
  because some test like @{"colour" LINK "What_are_Colours"} gradients require a big @{"palette" LINK "What_are_Colours"}.

     In order to do proper comparisons you monitor should have been on
  for 20-30 minutes period,  this is needed to heat up the  components
  inside and bring the monitor into stable state.

     The first screen that is presented to you is used to check screens
  size and position, @{"focus" LINK "What_is_Focus"} and @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"},  and to adjust @{"brightness" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"}
  and @{"contrast" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"}.

@ENDNODE







@REMARK 				--- TOOLS ---







@NODE "Tools" "Tools at disposal"

  @{b}Tools at disposal@{ub}
  @{b}=================@{ub}

     After  you  have select a screenmode a screen is opened and a small menu
  with the following options:


            @{bg fill}[·]        @{fg shine}Monitor Test - 800 x 600 x 24 bit@{fg text}        [8]@{bg back}
            @{"   Screenmode    " LINK "Screenmode"    } @{"      Moire      " LINK "Moire_Tools"      } @{"   Readability   " LINK "Readability_Tools"}
            @{"     Colour      " LINK "Colour_Tools"  } @{"      Focus      " LINK "Focus_Tools"      } @{"       Bar       " LINK "Bar_Tools"}
            @{"    Geometry     " LINK "Geometry_Tools"} @{"   Convergence   " LINK "Convergence_Tools"} @{"     Contrast    " LINK "Contrast_Tools"}


   - Hit the window close gadget [·] to quit this tool. 

   - Hit the window depth gadget [8] to hide the GUI for full screen display.
     Pressing the left mouse button anywhere on the screen will bring it back.

   - The @{"Resolution Tools" LINK "Resolution_Tools"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Screenmode" "Screenmode"

  @{b}Screenmode@{ub}
  @{b}==========@{ub}

     This button is used to change screen @{"resolution" LINK "What_is_Resolution"} and @{"colour" LINK "What_are_colours"} depth.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Colour_Tools" "Colour Tools"

  @{b}Colour Tools@{ub}
  @{b}============@{ub}

   * How are the @{"Colour" LINK "What_are_Colours"} tools used ?

     - Pure white is used for testing of white uniformity and flickering

     - Primary @{"colours" LINK "What_are_Colours"} are used for testing @{"colour" LINK "What_are_Colours"} uniformity, colour purity
       and flickering

     - Black is used is for testing of black level or "cut-off"


   * What can you do ?

     @{" Degaussing                                   " LINK "Degaussing"               }
     @{" Change the monitor's direction               " LINK "Change_the_monitor"       }
     @{" Nearby equipment                             " LINK "Nearby_equipment"         }

                   ONLY FOR SPECIALISTS

     @{" Adjust black level or `cut-off'              " LINK "Adjust_black_level"       }
     @{" Adjust high level                            " LINK "Adjust_high_level"        }
     @{" Badly aligned colours                        " LINK "Badly_aligned_colours"    }

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Geometry_Tools" "Geometry Tools"

  @{b}Geometry Tools@{ub}
  @{b}==============@{ub}

     The  geometry  parameters are affected by the @{"resolution" LINK "What_is_Resolution"} you use on your
  monitor.   This means that you will have to adjust your monitor for all the
  different @{"resolution" LINK "What_is_Resolution"} you use.  If your monitor has the capability to store
  more  than  one set of adjustments you shall use this program to adjust and
  store these adjustments for all the different resolutions you use.  If your
  monitor  can  not  store  such  adjustments  you should try to use only one
  resolution,  if  possible.   If this is not possible you can choose between
  either  adjusting your monitor for your most critical or most commonly used
  resolution,  or  readjusting  your  monitor when you change the @{"resolution" LINK "What_is_Resolution"}.


   * How the geometry tools are used ?

     Use this test pattern to adjust and check the picture's size,  position,
  pincushion  or  barrel,  tilt  or  rotation,  trapezoid,  orthogonality  or
  parallelogram.


    * Size and position

     Adjust  the  size  and position controls, so that the broken line almost
  disappears  behind  the  screen  bezel.  If the shape of the broken line is
  distorted,  try  to  adjust  other  parameters (trapezoid, tilt, pincushion
  etc.)  The  inner  circle  should  be perfectly round.  Measure the picture
  width and height.  The aspect ratio should be 4/3 (width/height).  If it is
  not, readjust the picture size slightly.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Moire_Tools" "Moire Tools"

  @{b}Moire Tools@{ub}
  @{b}===========@{ub}

   * How are the @{"Moire" LINK "What_is_moire"} tools used ?

     Look  for  waves,  wisps,  bundles and shimmers of intensity variations.
  Use  all the  test tools  to  check for @{"moire" LINK "What_is_moire"}, as the visibility of @{"moire" LINK "What_is_moire"}
  patterns varies with pattern and colour.


   * What can you do ?

     @{" Adjust focus control                          " LINK "Adjust_focus_control"     }
     @{" Change image size                             " LINK "Change_image_size"        }
     @{" Change resolution                             " LINK "Change_resolution"        }
     @{" Don't use grey or dark grey (dim) backgrounds " LINK "Dont_use_grey"            }
     @{" External filters                              " LINK "External filters"         }

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Focus_Tools" "Focus Tools"

  @{b}Focus Tools@{ub}
  @{b}===========@{ub}

   * How are the @{"Focus" LINK "What_is_Focus"} tools used ?

     The  @{"focus" LINK "What_is_Focus"}  tools display special patterns in each corner of the screen,
  and  in the centre.  The patterns are displayed in black on white, followed
  by  the  main colours on white.  This is a difficult test for most monitors
  when  close  to  their  rated  @{"resolution" LINK "What_is_Resolution"}.  In  particular,  watch out for
  differences between the centre and the corners.

   * What can you do ?

     @{" Adjust focus control, if there is one        " LINK "Adjust_focus_control"     }
     @{" Adjust the picture size                      " LINK "Adjust_the_picture"       }
     @{" Decrease the contrast                        " LINK "Decrease_the_contrast"    }
     @{" Use different colours                        " LINK "Use_different_colours"    }

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Convergence_Tools" "Convergence Tools"

  @{b}Convergence Tools@{ub}
  @{b}=================@{ub}

   * How are the @{"Convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"} tools used ?

     Click the button to change colours.

     Use this test pattern to check the @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"} error.


   * What can you do ?

     Read the owner's manual for the monitor.
 
     @{" Degaussing                                   " LINK "Degaussing"               }

     @{" Change image position                        " LINK "Change_image_position"    }
     @{" Change image size                            " LINK "Change_image_size"        }
     @{" Change resolution                            " LINK "Change_resolution"        }
     @{" Colour combinations                          " LINK "Colour_combinations"      }
     @{" Use different colours                        " LINK "Use_different_colours"    }

     @{" Adjustment of dynamic convergence            " LINK "Adjustment_of_dynamic"    }
     @{" Adjustment of static convergence             " LINK "Adjustment_of_static"     }

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Readability_Tools" "Moire Tools"

  @{b}Readability Tools@{ub}
  @{b}=================@{ub}

   * How are the Readability tools used ?

     Use this  pattern  to  check whether text is readable across the screen.
  The  text should be readable, and all parts of each letter should be clear.
  If  there  are alignment  problems you might notice @{"colour" LINK "What_are_Colours"} fringing or bad
  @{"focus" LINK "What_is_Focus"};  in  any  case  the  text  will  not  appear  sharp,  possibly  even
  unreadable.

     Note:   If you have too high a @{"resolution" LINK "What_is_Resolution"} on a small screen, it will be
             extremely  difficult  to  get  readable  text  as  the alignment
             tolerances are too tight.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Bar_Tools" "Screen Regulation Tools"

  @{b}Bar Tools@{ub}
  @{b}=========@{ub}

   * How are the @{"Screen Regulation" LINK "What_is_Screen_Regulation"} tools used ?

     After pressing the  Bar  button  your screen should start to automaticly
  redraw every 0.5 second and the picture will start to blink. While the test
  is working, clicking the left mouse button will change the pattern to a new
  one,  and another click will return you to the main menu.   During the test
  phase check the  white lines  on the left and right sides.  The blinking is
  merely used to make the effect easier to detect.   So if your screen starts
  to jump and get distored you can try the following:


   * What can you do ?

     @{" Reduce the background intensity              " LINK "Reduce_the_background"    }
     @{" Reduce the brightness and contrast           " LINK "Reduce_the_brightness"    }
     @{" Use different colours                        " LINK "Use_different_colours"    }
     @{" Use primary colours                          " LINK "Use_primary_colours"      }

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Contrast_Tools" "Brightness and Contrast Tools"

  @{b}Brightness and Contrast Tools@{ub}
  @{b}=============================@{ub}

     Please note  that this test  works only in 64 or  more @{"colour" LINK "What_are_Colours"} modes  and
  with  hardware  that can handle  8 bits  per primary @{"colour" LINK "What_are_Colours"},  otherwise the
  percentage boxes in the middle will not appear or show wrong values.

   * How are the @{"Brightness" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} and @{"Contrast" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} tools used ?

     The @{"brightness" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} control of your monitor determines the black level of the
  picture.   The  @{"contrast" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} control determines the white level of the picture.
  (The  video  amplifier's  gain.)  Using  this  test  pattern  you  can make
  recommended adjustments to your monitor settings.


   * @{"Brightness" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} adjustment

     The @{"brightness" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"}  control  should  be  used  to adjust the low level light
  output from your monitor for different ambient light conditions.

     Use  the  control  to  increase  the  @{"brightness" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"},  until you can see the
  background  (the  areas intended to be black) and all the dark grey squares
  marked  1-6%.   Decrease  it  again until you can just distinguish the dark
  grey squares brighter than 1-3%.

  If you set the @{"brightness" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} control too high the monitor cannot produce black.

     If you set the @{"brightness" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} control too low (blacker than black), then the
  dimmer grays will be lost and will be reproduced as black.


   * @{"Contrast" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} adjustment

     The  @{"contrast" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} control should be used set a comfortable light output from
  your  monitor.  This level depends on your application (program) as well as
  on  the  ambient light.  If the ambient light has changed you should always
  start with adjusting the @{"brightness" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} control.

     You  can  use this test pattern to set the @{"contrast" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} control to a default
  position  (the best position for all the information for which you use your
  screen).   When  you  run  new  programs  you  should then use the @{"contrast" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"}
  control to set the light output from the screen to a comfortable level.

     Adjust  the @{"contrast" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} control so that all big squares are visible, sharp,
  and  clearly  distinct,  and  have graduated intensities.


   * Recommendations

     The light output of your screen can under certain conditions be affected
  by  the  @{"resolution" LINK "What_is_Resolution"}  you  are using.  This means that you might have to use
  different settings for the @{"brightness" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} and @{"contrast" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} controls if you use more
  than one @{"resolution" LINK "What_is_Resolution"}.

     It's  better  to  set the black level a little too low, and lose some of
  darkest  gray  tones, than too high, and lose a black background and a good
  @{"contrast" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} between black and white.

     If  your  desktop  or  regularly  used  software has a bright background
  @{"colour" LINK "What_are_Colours"}  you  shouldn't set the @{"contrast" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} control too high, as your eyes will
  then tire more quickly!

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Resolution_Tools" "Resolution Tools"

  @{b}Resolution Tools@{ub}
  @{b}================@{ub}

     This  tool  is  useful  for  checking  whether  the  CRT  is  capable of
  displaying  finely spaced lines across the entire CRT image area.   At this
  moment only vertical @{"resolution" LINK "What_is_Resolution"} can be checked on the main test screen.


   * Maximum @{"resolution" LINK "What_is_Resolution"}

     The maximum @{"resolution" LINK "What_is_Resolution"} depends on:

      - The CRT size
      - The dot pitch or aperture grill
      - The video amplifier's bandwidth
      - The dot frequency
      - The rise-fall time
      - The video adapter card

      and it is always a combination of these factors.


     The  most popular CRT sizes are 14", 15", 17", 20", and 21".The CRT size
  is  measured  as  the diagonal  dimension  of the tube. The visible area is
  always  smaller  than  the CRT's face value.  A 15" CRT, for example, gives
  you a visible area of 13.7" diagonally.

     Dot pitch is a measure of the shortest distance between two dots  of the
  same colour. The most common dot pitches are 0.31 mm, 0.28 mm, and 0.26 mm.

                 Low resolution.    Dot pitch 0.44 to 0.47 mm
              Medium resolution.    Dot pitch 0.32 to 0.43 mm
                High resolution.    Dot pitch 0.28 to 0.31 mm
           Ultrahigh resolution.    Dot pitch 0.21 to 0.27 mm

     The amplifier bandwidth is specified in -3dB points.

             Bandwidth:  Fmax - Fmin  (-3dB)

     It  is  however  more  realistic  to talk  about video dot frequency and
  rise/fall times.

     The dot frequency is twice the video frequency.

             1/PIXEL TIME -> DOTFREQUENCY.

     Example: 200 MHz dot frequency  ->
                   ->  pixel time is 5ns (1/200MHz)  ->
                        ->  100 MHz video signal frequency (1/(5 ns+5 ns)).

    The rise-fall time is one most important properties of a video amplifier.
  The factor between rise/fall times and bandwidth:

              0.35/(rise time) -> bandwidth.

     Example: 0.35/3.5 ns -> 100 MHz

@ENDNODE







@REMARK					 --- GLOSSARY ---






@NODE "Glossary" "Glossary"

  @{b}Glossary@{ub}
  @{b}========@{ub}

     This  section  list  most  of  the special words used in this guide with
  detailed  information on some of  the topics.  I hope it is useful since it
  took a lot of time to write this guide in the first place.

     @{" What are Colours ?                   " LINK "What_are_Colours"          }
     @{" What is Brightness and Contrast ?    " LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"   }
     @{" What is Convergence ?                " LINK "What_is_Convergence"       }
     @{" What is Focus ?                      " LINK "What_is_Focus"             }
     @{" What is Moire ?                      " LINK "What_is_Moire"             }
     @{" What is Resolution ?                 " LINK "What_is_Resolution"        }
     @{" What is Screen Regulation ?          " LINK "What_is_Screen_Regulation" }

@ENDNODE

@NODE "What_are_Colours" "What are Colours ?"

  @{b}What are Colours ?@{ub}
  @{b}==================@{ub}

   * What are Colours ?

     Colours  are  just  something that we see with our eyes.  This something
  constitutes  rays of light, i.e.  electromagnetic waves with wavelengths of
  between 380 nm and 780 nm.

     Your  eyes  pick  up  the  electromagnetic  waves,  and  your brain then
  translates them into that which we call "colour".  In other words:  Colours
  only  exist  inside  our  brains.   This means that one person may conceive
  colours slightly different from another.


   * How does the monitor make colours ?

     Monitors  use  what  is called "additive colour mixing".  This is due to
  the  fact  that  if we add red, green and blue light together we get white.
  This  is  exactly  what happens in a colour monitor.  When we want white on
  the  screen  we  turn  on the electron guns hitting the red, green and blue
  phosphors.  Together the phosphors will then emit white light.


   * How many colours ?


     16-colour modes

     To  produce  16  different  colours on your screen 4 bits/pixel of video
  memory  is needed.  If you are running your OS in a 16 colour mode you will
  see  dithered  patterns.  Switch to a 256 colour mode, which should produce
  much better results and sometimes doesn't use dithering.


     256-colour Modes

     To  produce  256  different colours on your screen 8 bits/pixel of video
  memory  is needed.  In 256 colour modes PC video boards can display any 256
  colours,  from  a  palette  with  a  total  of  262 144 available different
  colours.   Each  primary colour has 64 intensity levels.  This is also true
  for some old Amiga addon video cards like CyberVision64/3D, however the new
  B/CvisionPPC cards on the Permedia II chip can produce any 256 colours from
  a  full  24  bit  palette  and  thus  each primary colour has 256 intensity
  levels.   This  is  the reason why AGA is better for 256 colour modes as it
  offers 8 bits per primary colour and if you never new starting with OS3 and
  AGA  the  primary  colours  are  calculated  in  32  bit per primary colour
  (probably for future expansion and AAA chipset).


     High colour

     To  produce  65K different colours on your screen 16 bits/pixel of video
  memory  is  needed.   In  "High  Colour"  modes the video board can display
  either  32  768  colours  or  65  536  colours.  Each primary colour has 32
  intensity  levels,  except  for green, which in the 65K mode has 64 levels.
  To be able to use this colour modes you need at least 2M of video memory at
  a @{"resolution" LINK "What_is_Resolution"} of 1024 x 768.


     True colour

     To  produce  16.8M  different  colours  (more  than  the eye can readily
  distinguish)  on your screen 24 bits/pixel of video memory is needed.  Each
  primary  colour  has  256  intensity levels.  To be able to use this colour
  mode  you  need  at  least 2M of video memory at a @{"resolution" LINK "What_is_Resolution"} of 800 x 600.
  This  mode  is  sometimes  named 32 bit which is basicly the way of storing
  data  in  memory  and  the  extra  8  bits  a  waisted  in favour of speed.
  CyberGraphX offers a choice between 24 bit and 32 bit memory usage.


     HAM - Hold and modify colour modes

     This  is a special Amiga feature which allows to display 262 144 colours
  on a 8 bit deep screen from a palette of 262 144 (64 graduations per colour
  - 6 bits) on AGA hardware or 4 096 out of 4 096 colours (16 graduations per
  colour  -  4  bits)  on  ECS  hardware on a 6 bit deep screen.  This is the
  reason why it is also known as 18 bit and 12 bit true colour screenmodes.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Brightness_and_Contrast" "What is Brightness and Contrast ?"

  @{b}What is Brightness and Contrast ?@{ub}
  @{b}=================================@{ub}

   * How light is produced on your monitor

     A  so  called  video  signal  is sent from the control-circuitry in your
  computer  to  the  monitor, telling the monitor both where on the screen to
  place  the  light  dot,  and  the  intended  light output ranging from zero
  (black)  to  maximum light output.  In the monitor this signal is converted
  to light on the monitor screen.


   * Why use brightness and contrast control ?

     There  are  normally  two  controls  for  setting  the light output of a
  monitor.    They   are   called   the   Brightness  and  Contrast  controls
  respectively.   The brightness control is used to adjust the video signal's
  zero-level  to  equal black on the monitor screen.  The contrast control is
  then  used  to set the amplification of the video signal, or in practice to
  set  the  light  output  on the monitor screen to a comfortable level.  The
  brightness  control  is used to adjust the low light output levels, and the
  contrast  control  to adjust the ratio between the low and high level light
  outputs.   Both  of  these adjustments are influenced by the ambient light,
  the application (program) being used, as well as by the operator's personal
  preferences.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "What_is_Convergence" "What is Convergence (Misconvergence) ?"

  @{b}What is Convergence (Misconvergence) ?@{ub}
  @{b}======================================@{ub}

     A white line on the screen consists of three coloured lines:  Red, green
  and  blue.  If the screen does not have any convergence error the lines are
  exactly overlaid each other, and the resulting @{"colour" LINK "What_are_Colours"} is white.

     In case of a convergence error separate red, green and blue lines can be
  seen, instead of one white.  It is similar to an out of @{"focus" LINK "What_is_Focus"} image, except
  that you will see thin coloured fringes around the edges of image detail.

     There is a possibility of horizontal and vertical misconvergence

     The  convergence  error will vary for different locations on screen, and
  will  also  be  different  for  each of the primary @{"colours" LINK "What_are_Colours"}.  Generally the
  convergence will be best near the centre, and worst in the corners.  As you
  can see misconvergence also has a bad influence on @{"focus" LINK "What_is_Focus"}.


   * How to identify convergence ?

     It is easier to find the misconvergence positions if you use:

     1. The convergence test picture.

     2. The start-up test pattern crosshatch lines (red, blue)


     There is no misconvergence when @{"colours" LINK "What_are_Colours"} are on the same line.

     Horizontal misconvergence if @{"colours" LINK "What_are_Colours"} are not on the same vertical line. 

     Vertical misconvergence if @{"colours" LINK "What_are_Colours"} are not on the same horizontal line.


   * How to measure convergence ?

     Use the convergence test pattern.

     Service  staff and other  expert monitor  users can  use a convergence
   meter/convergence gauge.


   * How to measure convergence error ?

     1. Use the white crosshatch test pattern

     2. Adjust the @{"contrast" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} to near maximum

     3. Adjust  the  @{"brightness" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"}  so  that the background just disappears. These
        instructions have been for the Klein CM7AR convergence gauge, but other
        types of gauges can also be used.

     4. Place  the  gauge  on the line, with the mark 'Y' facing upwards,  when
        measuring a horizontal line.

     5. Place  the  gauge  on the line, with the mark 'X' facing upwards,  when
        measuring a vertical line.

     6. If the line has a convergence error,  the line in the window appears to
        be broken.

     7. Use knobs A and B to adjust the line so that it becomes continuous.

     8. If the readings are on opposite sides of zero the convergence  error is
        A + B (e.g. 0.2 + 0.1 -> 0.3).

     9. If  the readings are on the same side of zero the convergence  error is
        equal to A if A > B, and equal to B if B > A.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "What_is_Focus" "What is Focus ?"

  @{b}What is Focus ?@{ub}
  @{b}===============@{ub}

     There are monitors with good and bad focusing.

     A  badly  focused  monitor  gives rise to beam spread, especially in the
  corners.  Focus is not the only effect that influences the image sharpness,
  other  main  reasons  are  @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"},  blooming,  the  video  amplifier's
  bandwidth, and @{"resolution" LINK "What_is_Resolution"}.

   * Blooming - If you increase @{"brightness" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} to high, it will cause the beam to
                spread and if this  spreading is excessive,  the monitor will
                lose sharpness.

   * The amplifier bandwidth is specified in -3dB points.

               Bandwidth:  Fmax - Fmin (-3dB).

     It  is  however  more  realistic  to  talk about video dot frequency and
  rise/fall times.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "What_is_Moire" "What is Moire ?"

  @{b}What is Moire ?@{ub}
  @{b}===============@{ub}

     Moire  is a natural interference  phenomenon  that appears on all colour
  CRT  monitors.  It  is  due to an interference between the shadow mask  (or
  aperture grill) and the @{"resolution" LINK "What_is_Resolution"} used.
 
     Normally  you  can  see  some  ripples,  waves,  and  wisps of intensity
  fluctuations  superimposed  on  the  screen.  They mostly occur in displays
  that use finally focused beams.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "What_is_Resolution" "What is Resolution ?"

  @{b}What is Resolution ?@{ub}
  @{b}====================@{ub}

     This is a number of picture elements or pixels, that are used to produce
  an image on the display.  The pixel resolution of the image is specified by
  means of (a) the number of pixels in each horizontal row, which is the same
  as  how  many  vertical  lines  it  is  possible  to see (if the horizontal
  resolution   is   800   it   is  possible  to  see  400  white/black  lines
  [1pixel/1pixel]),  and  (b) the number of pixels in each vertical column on
  the  screen,  which is the same as how many horizontal lines it is possible
  to  see  (if  the  vertical  resolution  is  600  it is possible to see 300
  white/black  lines) [1pixel/1pixel]).  The nominally used formula is H x V.

     Examples:   640  x  480  ->    307 200 addressable pixels.
                 800  x  600  ->    480 000 addressable pixels.
                1600  x 1200  ->  1 920 000 addressable pixels.

    The  most  popular  desktop  resolutions  are 640x480, 800x600, 1024x768,
  1280x1024 and 1600x1200. They offer the preffered 1:1 pixel aspect on a 4:3
  aspect screens.

              PICTURE WIDTH / RESOLUTION -> THEORETICAL PIXEL SIZE

              MONITOR SIZE    RESOLUTION    THEORETICAL PIXEL SIZE

                   21"       1600 x 1200           0.25 mm
                             1280 x 1024           0.31 mm
                             1152 x  870           0.35 mm
                             1024 x  768           0.39 mm
                              832 x  624           0.48 mm
                              800 x  600           0.50 mm
                              640 x  480           0.63 mm

                   17"       1280 x 1024           0.25 mm
                             1152 x  870           0.27 mm
                             1024 x  768           0.31 mm
                              832 x  624           0.38 mm
                              800 x  600           0.39 mm
                              640 x  480           0.49 mm

                   15"       1024 x  768           0.27 mm
                              832 x  624           0.34 mm
                              800 x  600           0.35 mm
                              640 x  480           0.44 mm

@ENDNODE

@NODE "What_is_Screen_Regulation" "What is Screen Regulation ?"

  @{b}What is Screen Regulation ?@{ub}
  @{b}===========================@{ub}

     On  some  monitors  the  image  expands in bright areas and contracts in
  dimmer  areas.   This  happens  because the monitor has a poor high-voltage
  regulation.   This  effect  is  more  or  less visible in all monitors, but
  normally  more so in very cheap monitor models, as it is not inexpensive to
  design and manufacture a very good high-voltage regulation system.  If your
  monitor  has  a  very  bad  screen regulation, the picture "zooms" when you
  adjust the @{"brightness" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} control.  Examples of where this often occurs are bar
  graphs, screen and window title bars.

@ENDNODE








