@ENDNODE

@NODE "Safety_Instructions" "Safety Instructions"

  @{b}Safety Instructions@{ub}
  @{b}===================@{ub}

     Read these instructions in full.  Follow cautions and instructions given
   on the monitor.

     Do not attempt to service or open the monitor yourself.

     To prevent fire or shock hazard, do not expose this appliance to rain or
  moisture.   Never  let  objects of any kind enter into this monitor through
  cabinet  slots,  as  they  may  then come into contact with components with
  dangerous  voltage,  which could result in a fire or electric shock.  Never
  spill  liquid  of  any  kind  on the monitor.  Unplug the monitor for added
  protection,  when  it  is left unattended and unused for a longer period of
  time.    Do   not  use  any  attachments  not  recommended  by  your  sales
  representative, as they may give rise to hazards.

     If  the  monitor  is damaged it should immediately be unplugged from the
  power outlet.

     Connection to power system

     Do  not  connect  the power cord of the monitor to a power outlet with a
  voltage  or  frequency  that differs from that indicated on it's commercial
  label.   Always  use  a  grounded power outlet.  Use the attached specified
  power  cable, which will not interfere with radio and television reception.
  Do not expose the power cord to mechanical stress.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Adjust_focus_control" "Adjust focus control"

  @{b}Adjust focus control@{ub}
  @{b}====================@{ub}

     Adjust the @{"focus" LINK "What_is_Focus"} control so that the pattern becomes as sharp as possible.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Adjust_the_picture" "Adjust the picture size"

  @{b}Adjust the picture size@{ub}
  @{b}=======================@{ub}

     If the @{"focus" LINK "What_is_Focus"} in the corners is a major problem, readjust the picture size.

     See also:  @{"Convergence" link "What_is_Convergence"}, @{"Change image size" link "Change_image_size"} and @{"Change image position" link "Change_image_position"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Adjustment_of_dynamic" "Adjustment of dynamic convergence"

  @{b}Adjustment of dynamic convergence@{ub}
  @{b}=================================@{ub}

     The dynamic @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"} is usually adjusted by means of various internal
  potentiometers, which will vary the voltages to the deflection coils in the
  yoke  assembly.   Some  monitors  have dynamic @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"} controls.  These
  normally  divide  the  screen  into  zones, and make it possible to set the
  @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"} for each of these zones individually.

   START BY ADJUSTING/CHECKING ANY STATIC CONVERGENCE FOR PERFECT CONVERGENCE
                          AT THE CENTRE OF THE SCREEN.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Adjustment_of_static" "Adjustment of static convergence"

  @{b}Adjustment of static convergence@{ub}
  @{b}================================@{ub}

     The  static  @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"} is usually set by means of @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"} magnets,
  which  are  mounted  on  the yoke assembly on the neck of the picture tube.
  Some  monitors  also  have  one  or  two  @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"}  controls, which have
  influence  on  the  @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"}  over  the  entire  screen.   Each of these
  controls is used to converge the red and blue lines onto the green line, as
  closely  as possible.  If the monitor has two controls, one of these is for
  the vertical @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"} and the other for the horizontal @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Change_image_position" "Change image position"

  @{b}Change image position@{ub}
  @{b}=====================@{ub}

     The  @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"}  is  generally worst on the periphery of the image (one
  side or corner).  Shift the image away from the worst side or corner.  This
  will reduce the problem.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Change_image_size" "Change image size"

  @{b}Change image size@{ub}
  @{b}=================@{ub}

     The  @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"}  is  generally worst on the periphery of the image (one
  side  or  corner).  Resize the  image so that  it moves away from the worst
  side or corner.  This will reduce the problem.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Change_resolution" "Change resolution"

  @{b}Change resolution@{ub}
  @{b}=================@{ub}

     The  same @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"} error is not as visible at a low @{"resolution" LINK "What_is_Resolution"}, as at
  a high one, because the theoretical pixel size is then bigger.

     Example: A @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"} error of 0.30 mm is clearly visible if your pixel
              size is 0.25 mm, but the same error is not so bad if your pixel
              size is 0.40 mm.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Change_the_intensities" "Change the intensities of the system colours"

  @{b}Change the intensities of the system colours@{ub}
  @{b}============================================@{ub}

     Use  the  Palette  Prefs  tool  to  change the intensities of the system
  @{"colours" LINK "What_are_Colours"}.   (Starting  from  OS  3.5  instructions  can be found in the HTML
  documentation  of the AmigaOS or in the printed manual for older versions.)

     PS: On some  AGA  systems  you have reduce pure white from 255 to 240 to
  avoid problems in doublescan screenmodes.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Change_the_monitor" "Change the monitor's direction"

  @{b}Change the monitor's direction@{ub}
  @{b}==============================@{ub}

     Monitors  are  generally  adjusted  at the manufacturing facility facing
  east.   The  monitor  should  therefore  have  it's best @{"colour" LINK "What_are_Colours"} purity when
  facing in that direction.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Colour_combinations" "Colour combinations"

  @{b}Colour combinations@{ub}
  @{b}===================@{ub}

     You  can  use  different  @{"colour" LINK "What_are_Colours"} combinations, depending on what kind of
  @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"} error you have on your monitor.

     These combinations are:

                  Red  +  Blue  ->  Magenta
                Green  +  Blue  ->  Cyan
                Green  +  Red   ->  Yellow

     - If you have a RED-BLUE @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"} error 

       Do not use magenta, red and blue together, but instead use cyan, green
       and blue or yellow, green and red together.

     - If you have a RED-GREEN @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"} error 

       Do not use yellow, red and green together, but instead use cyan, green
       and blue or magenta, red and blue together.

     - If You have a GREEN-BLUE @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"} error 

       Do not use cyan, green and blue together, but instead use magenta, red
       and blue or yellow, green and red together.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Decrease_the_contrast" "Decrease the contrast"

  @{b}Decrease the contrast@{ub}
  @{b}=====================@{ub}

     Decreasing  the  @{"contrast" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"}  will  sharpen  the  image,  by  reducing  the
  thickness of the beam.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Degaussing" "Degaussing"

  @{b}Degaussing@{ub}
  @{b}==========@{ub}

     Degaussing  Stray magnetic fields can affect the @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"}.  Press the
  manual  degaussing  button  once.   If  your monitor does not have a manual
  degaussing  function  degaussing  will  be  performed  automatically.  This
  however only takes place if the monitor is powered on after having been off
  for half an hour.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Dont_use_grey" "Don't use grey or dark grey (dim) backgrounds"

  @{b}Don't use grey or dark grey (dim) backgrounds@{ub}
  @{b}=============================================@{ub}

     Use  white  background  colour.  This will increase the beam current and
  defocus  your  picture.   Check  the picture focusing by means of the @{"focus" LINK "What_is_Focus"}
  tools and/or the readability tools.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "External filters" "External filters"

  @{b}External filters@{ub}
  @{b}================@{ub}

     Some  external "low  radiation" gives rise to @{"moire" LINK "What_is_moire"}.  Check your monitor
  both with and without filter.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Nearby_equipment" "Nearby equipment"

  @{b}Nearby equipment@{ub}
  @{b}================@{ub}

     Any nearby equipment which generates a magnetic field, such as speakers,
  computers,  old-style telephones, external disk drives, CD-ROM units, etc.,
  can  affect  the  @{"colour" LINK "What_are_Colours"}  purity.  Make sure that you do not have any fans,
  external  power  transformers  (fluorescent  lights),  or  motor-driven  or
  solenoid actuated appliances near your monitor.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Reduce_the_background" "Reduce the background intensity"

  @{b}Reduce the background intensity@{ub}
  @{b}===============================@{ub}

     Use the Palette and Pattern Prefs to change background, for example from
  white to grey.  (Starting from OS 3.5 instructions can be found in the HTML
  documentation of the AmigaOS or in the printed manual for older versions.)

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Reduce_the_brightness" "Reduce the brightness and contrast"

  @{b}Reduce the brightness and contrast@{ub}
  @{b}==================================@{ub}

     Reduce  the  @{"brightness" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"}  and  @{"contrast" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"}.  This decreases the beam current
  level and reduces the effect.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Use_different_colours" "Use different colours"

  @{b}Use different colours@{ub}
  @{b}=====================@{ub}

     You  can  use  different  @{"colours" LINK "What_are_Colours"},  to  achieve  a good @{"contrast" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"}, as the
  @{"convergence" LINK "What_is_Convergence"}  error  is  not as visible at a lower @{"contrast" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} (and @{"brightness" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"})
  level.   Using a lower  @{"contrast" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} level  gives better  @{"focus" LINK "What_is_Focus"} then.   Use for
  example blue and cyan.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Use_primary_colours" "Use primary colours"

  @{b}Use primary colours@{ub}
  @{b}===================@{ub}

     White  is  made  up of all the three primary @{"colours" LINK "What_are_Colours"}, and will therefore
  load  the beam current three times more often than only red, green or blue.
  Secondary  @{"colours" LINK "What_are_Colours"}  like  magenta,  yellow, and cyan loads the beam current
  twice as often as the primary @{"colours" LINK "What_are_Colours"}.

@ENDNODE

@REMARK --- ONLY FOR SPECIALISTS ---

@NODE "Adjust_black_level" "Adjust black level or `cut-off'"

  @{b}Adjust black level or "cut-off"@{ub}
  @{b}===============================@{ub}

     THIS ROUTINE IS NOT RECOMMENDED UNLESS YOU HAVE AN INSTRUMENT SUCH AS A
              COLOUR ANALYSER.  CONTACT THE SERVICE ORGANIZATION

     The first  step consists of feeding the monitor a signal which is black.
  You  should  then  adjust  the @{"brightness" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} so that you can only just see the
  background  (2 cd/m2,  if you have a @{"colour" LINK "What_are_Colours"} analyser for this).  The second
  step  consists  of  setting the red, green and blue cut-off controls of the
  monitor,  until  the  @{"colour" LINK "What_are_Colours"}  analyser  indicates  that  the  @{"colour" LINK "What_are_Colours"}  is at
  "daylight" at low level.

     What  we  are  doing is to adjust the position of each of the individual
  curves  up  and  down,  until  we get the correct balance at low level.  In
  other words:  all three lines cross each other at low level.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Adjust_high_level" "Adjust high level"

  @{b}Adjust high level@{ub}
  @{b}=================@{ub}

       THIS IS NOT RECOMMENDED, IF YOU DON'T HAVE AN INSTRUMENT SUCH AS A
              COLOUR ANALYSER.  CONTACT THE SERVICE ORGANIZATION

     Feed  the monitor a white signal.  Use a @{"colour" LINK "What_are_Colours"} analyser to check if the
  @{"colour" LINK "What_are_Colours"} is "daylight" at the correct level, e.g.  100 cd/m2 (adjust by means
  of  the @{"contrast" LINK "Brightness_and_Contrast"} control).  Adjust the red, green and blue gain controls of
  the monitor until you have that colour.

     What  we  are  doing is to adjust the position of each of the individual
  curves up and down, until we get the correct balance at low and high level.
  In  other  words:  all three lines cross each other at low level and at the
  maximum light output level.

    REPEAT THE CUT-OFF ADJUSTMENTS, FOLLOWED BY THE WHITE LEVEL ADJUSTMENT,
           UNTIL YOU GET THE SAME COLOURS ON "BLACK" AND ON "WHITE".

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Badly_aligned_colours" "Badly aligned colours"

  @{b}Badly aligned colours@{ub}
  @{b}=====================@{ub}

     Here  you'll  see  how  the  light  output  of  the  red, green and blue
  phosphors varies with the beam current of the three electron guns.  This is
  a badly aligned monitor.

@ENDNODE





@REMARK 				--- MISC ---






@NODE "History" "History"

  @{b}History@{ub}
  @{b}=======@{ub}

  v0.9 (08/08/2008)   First release (Public) - Based on original Monitor Test v0.9
                      - All tests converted for 16:9 screens


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Notes" "Notes"

  @{b}Notes@{ub}
  @{b}=====@{ub}

  - I have  no plans to support overscan,  currently text overscan is used to
    form the picture.

  - Your screen has to be of a 16:9 aspect, use original Monitor Test for 4:3 screens.

  - You can hide the gui by the depth window gadget.  Clicking mouse anywhere
    on the screen will select the gui.

  - Do not  use  VisualPrefs and  Birdie on  Monitor Tests screen if problems
    arise with the intuition gui.

  - B/CVision software promoter has a lot of bugs!
    (Doesn't setup colours correctly, doesn't show all drawing operations,
    doesn't show full screen - left 4 pixels of the screen are missing ;-)

  - Use some border blanker on native displays for better results.

@ENDNODE

